# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: resizable-array-structure
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] In computer science, an **array** is a data structure consisting of a collection of *elements* (values or variables), of the same memory size, each identified by at least one *array index* or *key*, the collection of which may be a tuple, known as an index tuple.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] In general, an array is a mutable and linear collection of elements with the same data type.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] An array is stored such that the position (memory address) of each element can be computed from its index tuple by a mathematical formula.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] The simplest type of data structure is a linear array, also called a one-dimensional array.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] For example, an array of ten 32-bit (4-byte) integer variables, with indices 0 through 9, may be stored as ten words at memory addresses 2000, 2004, 2008, ..., 2036, (in hexadecimal: `0x7D0`, `0x7D4`, `0x7D8`, ..., `0x7F4`) so that the element with index *i* has the address 2000 + (*i* × 4).
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] The memory address of the first element of an array is called first address, foundation address, or base address.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Because the mathematical concept of a matrix can be represented as a two-dimensional grid, two-dimensional arrays are also sometimes called "matrices".
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] In some cases the term "vector" is used in computing to refer to an array, although tuples rather than vectors are the more mathematically correct equivalent.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Tables are often implemented in the form of arrays, especially lookup tables; the word "table" is sometimes used as a synonym of array.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Arrays are among the oldest and most important data structures, and are used by almost every program.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] They are also used to implement many other data structures, such as lists and strings.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] They effectively exploit the addressing logic of computers.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] In most modern computers and many external storage devices, the memory is a one-dimensional array of words, whose indices are their addresses.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Processors, especially vector processors, are often optimized for array operations.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Arrays are useful mostly because the element indices can be computed at run time.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Among other things, this feature allows a single iterative statement to process arbitrarily many elements of an array.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] For that reason, the elements of an array data structure are required to have the same size and should use the same data representation.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] The set of valid index tuples and the addresses of the elements (and hence the element addressing formula) are usually, but not always, fixed while the array is in use.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] The term "array" may also refer to an array data type, a kind of data type provided by most high-level programming languages that consists of a collection of values or variables that can be selected by one or more indices computed at run-time.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Array types are often implemented by array structures; however, in some languages they may be implemented by hash tables, linked lists, search trees, or other data structures.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] The term is also used, especially in the description of algorithms, to mean associative array or "abstract array", a theoretical computer science model (an abstract data type or ADT) intended to capture the essential properties of arrays.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] The first digital computers used machine-language programming to set up and access array structures for data tables, vector and matrix computations, and for many other purposes.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] John von Neumann wrote the first array-sorting program (merge sort) in 1945, during the building of the first stored-program computer.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Array indexing was originally done by self-modifying code, and later using index registers and indirect addressing.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Some mainframes designed in the 1960s, such as the Burroughs B5000 and its successors, used memory segmentation to perform index-bounds checking in hardware.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Assembly languages generally have no special support for arrays, other than what the machine itself provides.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] The earliest high-level programming languages, including FORTRAN (1957), Lisp (1958), COBOL (1960), and ALGOL 60 (1960), had support for multi-dimensional arrays, and so has C (1972).
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] In C++ (1983), class templates exist for multi-dimensional arrays whose dimension is fixed at runtime as well as for runtime-flexible arrays.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Arrays are used to implement mathematical vectors and matrices, as well as other kinds of rectangular tables.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Many databases, small and large, consist of (or include) one-dimensional arrays whose elements are records.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Arrays are used to implement other data structures, such as lists, heaps, hash tables, deques, queues, stacks, strings, and VLists.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] One or more large arrays are sometimes used to emulate in-program dynamic memory allocation, particularly memory pool allocation.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Historically, this has sometimes been the only way to allocate "dynamic memory" portably.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Arrays can be used to determine partial or complete control flow in programs, as a compact alternative to (otherwise repetitive) multiple `IF` statements.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] In this context, they are known as control tables and are used in conjunction with a purpose-built interpreter whose control flow is altered according to values contained in the array.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] The array may contain subroutine pointers (or relative subroutine numbers that can be acted upon by SWITCH statements) that direct the path of the execution of the program.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] When data objects are stored in an array, individual objects are selected by an index that is usually a non-negative scalar integer.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] An index *maps* the array value to a stored object.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] The first element of the array is indexed by subscript of 0.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] The first element of the array is indexed by subscript of 1.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] The base index of an array can be freely chosen.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Using zero based indexing is the design choice of many influential programming languages, including C, Java and Lisp.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] This leads to simpler implementation where the subscript refers to an offset from the starting position of an array, so the first element has an offset of zero.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Arrays can have multiple dimensions, thus it is not uncommon to access an array using multiple indices.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] For example, a two-dimensional array `A` with three rows and four columns might provide access to the element at the 2nd row and 4th column by the expression `A[1][3]` in the case of a zero-based indexing system.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Thus two indices are used for a two-dimensional array, three for a three-dimensional array, and *n* for an *n*-dimensional array.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] The number of indices needed to specify an element is called the dimension, dimensionality, or rank of the array.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] In standard arrays, each index is restricted to a certain range of consecutive integers (or consecutive values of some enumerated type), and the address of an element is computed by a "linear" formula on the indices.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] A one-dimensional array (or single dimension array) is a type of linear array.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Accessing its elements involves a single subscript which can either represent a row or column index.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] As an example consider the C declaration `int a[10];` which declares a one-dimensional array named `a` of ten integers.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Here, the array can store ten elements of type `int` .
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] This array has indices starting from zero through nine.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] For example, the expressions `a[0]` and `a[9]` are the first and last elements respectively.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] For a vector with linear addressing, the element with index *i* is located at the address *B* + *c* · *i*, where *B* is a fixed *base address* and *c* a fixed constant, sometimes called the *address increment* or *stride*.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] If the valid element indices begin at 0, the constant *B* is simply the address of the first element of the array.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] For this reason, the C programming language specifies that array indices always begin at 0; and many programmers will call that element "zeroth" rather than "first".
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] However, one can choose the index of the first element by an appropriate choice of the base address *B*.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] For example, if the array has five elements, indexed 1 through 5, and the base address *B* is replaced by *B* + 30*c*, then the indices of those same elements will be 31 to 35.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] If the numbering does not start at 0, the constant *B* may not be the address of any element.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] For a multidimensional array, the element with indices *i*,*j* would have address *B* + *c* · *i* + *d* · *j*, where the coefficients *c* and *d* are the *row* and *column address increments*, respectively.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] This means that array a has 2 rows and 3 columns, and the array is of integer type.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Here we can store 6 elements they will be stored linearly but starting from first row linear then continuing with second row.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] This formula requires only *k* multiplications and *k* additions, for any array that can fit in memory.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Moreover, if any coefficient is a fixed power of 2, the multiplication can be replaced by bit shifting.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] The coefficients *c**k* must be chosen so that every valid index tuple maps to the address of a distinct element.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] If the minimum legal value for every index is 0, then *B* is the address of the element whose indices are all zero.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] As in the one-dimensional case, the element indices may be changed by changing the base address *B*.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Thus, if a two-dimensional array has rows and columns indexed from 1 to 10 and 1 to 20, respectively, then replacing *B* by *B* + *c*1 − 3*c*2 will cause them to be renumbered from 0 through 9 and 4 through 23, respectively.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Taking advantage of this feature, some languages (like FORTRAN 77) specify that array indices begin at 1, as in mathematical tradition while other languages (like Fortran 90, Pascal and Algol) let the user choose the minimum value for each index.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] The addressing formula is completely defined by the dimension *d*, the base address *B*, and the increments *c*1, *c*2, ..., *c**k*.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] It is often useful to pack these parameters into a record called the array's descriptor, stride vector, or dope vector.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] The size of each element, and the minimum and maximum values allowed for each index may also be included in the dope vector.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] The dope vector is a complete handle for the array, and is a convenient way to pass arrays as arguments to procedures.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Many useful array slicing operations (such as selecting a sub-array, swapping indices, or reversing the direction of the indices) can be performed very efficiently by manipulating the dope vector.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Often the coefficients are chosen so that the elements occupy a contiguous area of memory.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Even if arrays are always created with contiguous elements, some array slicing operations may create non-contiguous sub-arrays from them.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] There are two systematic compact layouts for a two-dimensional array.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] For arrays with three or more indices, "row major order" puts in consecutive positions any two elements whose index tuples differ only by one in the *last* index.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] "Column major order" is analogous with respect to the *first* index.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] In systems which use processor cache or virtual memory, scanning an array is much faster if successive elements are stored in consecutive positions in memory, rather than sparsely scattered.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] This is known as spatial locality, which is a type of locality of reference.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Many algorithms that use multidimensional arrays will scan them in a predictable order.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] A programmer (or a sophisticated compiler) may use this information to choose between row- or column-major layout for each array.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] For example, when computing the product *A*·*B* of two matrices, it would be best to have *A* stored in row-major order, and *B* in column-major order.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Static arrays have a size that is fixed when they are created and consequently do not allow elements to be inserted or removed.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] However, by allocating a new array and copying the contents of the old array to it, it is possible to effectively implement a *dynamic* version of an array; see dynamic array.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] If this operation is done infrequently, insertions at the end of the array require only amortized constant time.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Some array data structures do not reallocate storage, but do store a count of the number of elements of the array in use, called the count or size.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] This effectively makes the array a dynamic array with a fixed maximum size or capacity; Pascal strings are examples of this.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] More complicated (non-linear) formulas are occasionally used.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] For a compact two-dimensional triangular array, for instance, the addressing formula is a polynomial of degree 2.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Both *store* and *select* take (deterministic worst case) constant time.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Arrays take linear (O(*n*)) space in the number of elements *n* that they hold.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] In an array with element size *k* and on a machine with a cache line size of B bytes, iterating through an array of *n* elements requires the minimum of ceiling(*nk*/B) cache misses, because its elements occupy contiguous memory locations.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] This is roughly a factor of B/*k* better than the number of cache misses needed to access *n* elements at random memory locations.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Libraries provide low-level optimized facilities for copying ranges of memory (such as memcpy) which can be used to move contiguous blocks of array elements significantly faster than can be achieved through individual element access.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] The speedup of such optimized routines varies by array element size, architecture, and implementation.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Memory-wise, arrays are compact data structures with no per-element overhead.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] There may be a per-array overhead (e.g., to store index bounds) but this is language-dependent.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] It can also happen that elements stored in an array require *less* memory than the same elements stored in individual variables, because several array elements can be stored in a single word; such arrays are often called *packed* arrays.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] An extreme (but commonly used) case is the bit array, where every bit represents a single element.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] A single octet can thus hold up to 256 different combinations of up to 8 different conditions, in the most compact form.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Array accesses with statically predictable access patterns are a major source of data parallelism.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Dynamic arrays or growable arrays are similar to arrays but add the ability to insert and delete elements; adding and deleting at the end is particularly efficient.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] However, they reserve linear (Θ(*n*)) additional storage, whereas arrays do not reserve additional storage.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Associative arrays provide a mechanism for array-like functionality without huge storage overheads when the index values are sparse.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] For example, an array that contains values only at indexes 1 and 2 billion may benefit from using such a structure.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Specialized associative arrays with integer keys include Patricia tries, Judy arrays, and van Emde Boas trees.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Balanced trees require O(log *n*) time for indexed access, but also permit inserting or deleting elements in O(log *n*) time, whereas growable arrays require linear (Θ(*n*)) time to insert or delete elements at an arbitrary position.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Linked lists allow constant time removal and insertion in the middle but take linear time for indexed access.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Their memory use is typically worse than arrays, but is still linear.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] An Iliffe vector is an alternative to a multidimensional array structure.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] It uses a one-dimensional array of references to arrays of one dimension less.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] For two dimensions, in particular, this alternative structure would be a vector of pointers to vectors, one for each row(pointer on c or c++).
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Thus an element in row *i* and column *j* of an array *A* would be accessed by double indexing (*A*[*i*][*j*] in typical notation).
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] This alternative structure allows jagged arrays, where each row may have a different size—or, in general, where the valid range of each index depends on the values of all preceding indices.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] It also saves one multiplication (by the column address increment) replacing it by a bit shift (to index the vector of row pointers) and one extra memory access (fetching the row address), which may be worthwhile in some architectures.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] The *dimension* of an array is the number of indices needed to select an element.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Thus, if the array is seen as a function on a set of possible index combinations, it is the dimension of the space of which its domain is a discrete subset.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Thus a one-dimensional array is a list of data, a two-dimensional array is a rectangle of data, a three-dimensional array a block of data, etc.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] This should not be confused with the dimension of the set of all matrices with a given domain, that is, the number of elements in the array.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] For example, an array with 5 rows and 4 columns is two-dimensional, but such matrices form a 20-dimensional space.
[src:resizable-array-structure/array-data-structure] Similarly, a three-dimensional vector can be represented by a one-dimensional array of size three.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] In computer science, a **circular buffer**, **circular queue**, **cyclic buffer** or **ring buffer** is a data structure that uses a single, fixed-size buffer as if it were connected end-to-end.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] This structure lends itself easily to buffering data streams.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] There were early circular buffer implementations in hardware.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] A circular buffer first starts out empty and has a set length.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] If two elements are removed, the two oldest values inside of the circular buffer would be removed.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] Circular buffers use FIFO (*first in, first out*) logic.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] In the example, 1 & 2 were the first to enter the circular buffer, they are the first to be removed, leaving 3 inside of the buffer.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] When elements get removed, only the read-pointer moves to the next element.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] Removed elements are still in the buffer, waiting to get overwritten by new elements.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] A property of the circular buffer is that when it is full and a subsequent write is performed, then it starts overwriting the oldest data.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] Alternatively, the routines that manage the buffer could prevent overwriting the data and return an error or raise an exception.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] Whether or not data is overwritten is up to the semantics of the buffer routines or the application using the circular buffer.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] The useful property of a circular buffer is that it does not need to have its elements shuffled around when one is consumed.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] (If a non-circular buffer were used then it would be necessary to shift all elements when one is consumed.) In other words, the circular buffer is well-suited as a FIFO (*first in, first out*) buffer while a standard, non-circular buffer is well suited as a LIFO (*last in, first out*) buffer.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] Circular buffering makes a good implementation strategy for a queue that has fixed maximum size.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] Should a maximum size be adopted for a queue, then a circular buffer is a completely ideal implementation; all queue operations are constant time.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] However, expanding a circular buffer requires shifting memory, which is comparatively costly.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] For arbitrarily expanding queues, a linked list approach may be preferred instead.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] In some situations, an overwriting circular buffer can be used, e.g. in multimedia.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] If the buffer is used as the bounded buffer in the producer–consumer problem then it is probably desired for the producer (e.g., an audio generator) to overwrite old data if the consumer (e.g., the sound card) is unable to momentarily keep up.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] Also, the LZ77 family of lossless data compression algorithms operates on the assumption that strings seen more recently in a data stream are more likely to occur soon in the stream.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] Implementations store the most recent data in a circular buffer.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] In the beginning the indexes end and start are set to 0.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] The circular buffer write operation writes an element to the end index position and the end index is incremented to the next buffer position.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] The circular buffer read operation reads an element from the start index position and the start index is incremented to the next buffer position.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] The start and end indexes alone are not enough to distinguish between buffer full or empty state while also utilizing all buffer slots, but can be if the buffer only has a maximum in-use size of Length − 1.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] In this case, the buffer is empty if the start and end indexes are equal and full when the in-use size is Length − 1.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] Another solution is to have another integer count that is incremented at a write operation and decremented at a read operation.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] Then checking for emptiness means testing count equals 0 and checking for fullness means testing count equals Length.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] The following source code is a C implementation together with a minimal test.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] Function put() puts an item in the buffer, function get() gets an item from the buffer.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] A circular-buffer implementation may be optimized by mapping the underlying buffer to two contiguous regions of virtual memory.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] When the read offset is advanced into the second virtual-memory region, both offsets—read and write—are decremented by the length of the underlying buffer.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] Perhaps the most common version of the circular buffer uses 8-bit bytes as elements.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] Some implementations of the circular buffer use fixed-length elements that are bigger than 8-bit bytes—16-bit integers for audio buffers, 53-byte ATM cells for telecom buffers, etc.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] Each item is contiguous and has the correct data alignment, so software reading and writing these values can be faster than software that handles non-contiguous and non-aligned values.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] Ping-pong buffering can be considered a very specialized circular buffer with exactly two large fixed-length elements.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] The *bip buffer* (bipartite buffer) is very similar to a circular buffer, except it always returns contiguous blocks which can be variable length.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] This offers nearly all the efficiency advantages of a circular buffer while maintaining the ability for the buffer to be used in APIs that only accept contiguous blocks.
[src:resizable-array-structure/circular-buffer] Fixed-sized compressed circular buffers use an alternative indexing strategy based on elementary number theory to maintain a fixed-sized compressed representation of the entire data sequence.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] In computer science, a **double-ended queue** (abbreviated to **deque** — /dɛk/ *DEK*), is an abstract data type that serves as a container, with a restricted access to the stored items.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] As a generalization of both the stack and the queue, the deque may have similar functions as a data buffer: it can be use both as a *retainer* (queue), or for backtracking (stack).
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] However it offers greater flexibility in managing the order of elements and some algorithms are based on its functionalities.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] The double-ended queue is most often presented as a generalized queue, which gives its name.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] It is a queue that "allows insertions and deletions at both ends".
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] The deque is also described as a generalization of the stack abstract data structure, as "two stacks joined together at the base", with a shared bottom item, or as a combination of both the stack and the queue.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] And then conversely the queue and the stack are restricted forms of the deque.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Different analogies with real-world objects are used to described the deque.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] It is compared to a "deck of cards" with which the structure shares some properties and the pronunciation.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] The deque is also likened to a "necklace with beads that can be added and/or removed at either end".
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Like the queue, it is depicted as a set of items lined up in a pipe open at both ends ; unlike the queue, the items can move in both direction in the pipe.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] The "railroad model" introduced by Knuth (after "Dijkstra's shunting yard") focus on the similarity with the queue, with one input and one output, and switches to select the side of the deque to be accessed.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] The main operations on a deque are said to act on either *side* (or *end*) of the structure: addition of an item into the collection (*enqueue*), removal of an item *(dequeue*), and reading of an item (*peek*).
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] At at a given point in time only two items can be accessed, from either side of the deque, based on the history of the structure.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] The designated item on one side is either the latest one that has been inserted on this side (LIFO behavior), or, — if there is none —, the oldest one that has been inserted on the other side (FIFO behavior).
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] This service policy gives the structure more flexibility and versatility, but it is also more difficult to fathom and use.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Each approach has its merits: the first one allows the overloading of the operations but needs to have different names on each sides, while the second one simplifies the interface by halving the number of operations and allows to make use of the symmetry of the structure.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Despite their limitations these sub-types have many applications and some of their implementations may be simpler.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] After Knuth, these structures are often described as different forms of restricted *linear lists* , or sequences.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] They maintain the contained elements in a given order while only allow access to some of them: the first one and/or the last one in the sequence.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] However other authors object that they "hide their internal dynamism from the user" and only the common implementations are linear.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] For example, a deque can be implemented with a min-max heap, or with a set: before an item is inserted, it is tagged with a integer used as its value in the heap, and that depends on the history of the container.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] The stored elements in a heap are not ordered and their locations depend on the internal state of the structure.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Another common restricted access structure is the priority queue, which is not a linear structure.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] The deque can be generalized by the addition of some operations: a deque with heap order, or *mindeque*, allows the *find-min* operation.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Fast or even optimal catenation is also possible.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Some authors consider the deque structure as being of little use, less useful than its restricted forms, especially the stack and the queue.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] The deque can then be seen "as either a superqueue or a superstack".
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] "If two nodes are inserted at one end and removed from the other, they will exit in queue order.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] If they are both removed from the entry end, then they exit in stack order.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] "a data structure looking for an application!", cited by Roy S.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] The deque is here considered as unbounded: it can contain an unlimited (and undefined) number of items.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] A bounded deque is possible, and requires a slightly different specification, but when an overflow occurs the behavior depends on the implementation: error value, exception, deletion, etc.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] As a linear structure, the deque can be specified in terms of catenation (noted "~") of sequences and singleton sequences (noted "< ... >").
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] An axiomatic specification (or algebraic) of the deque can be obtained by extending and merging those of the stack and the queue.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] (see Nguyen thesis for an alternative formulation).
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Conversely the stack and the queue can be specified axiomatically in terms of the deque.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] The term *deque* (/dɛk/ *DEK*) is used as an abbreviation of Double-Ended QUEue.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] *Dequeue* is sometimes used but can be confusing as the term is also used for the operation of removing an element of the deque.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] A deque may also be called a *head-tail linked list*, though properly this refers to a specific implementation.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] An output-restricted deque may be designated as *steque* (for stack-ended queue).
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] There is no standard vocabulary associated with deques.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] The terms *enqueue* and *dequeue*, borrowed from the queue structure, generally denote the basic operations on a deque, on either end.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] But papers and actual implementations often use different names.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Unlike the associated data structures the deque is symmetrical.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] The full name of an operation may be a combination of the name of the basic operation and the name of the side: e.g.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Terms from different analogies may be associated in a single context: *append* and *pop*, *push* and *shift*, or *front* and *tail*.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Finally some programming languages use even different names based on the underlying data structure.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Also generally implemented are *"peek"* operations, which return the value at one end without dequeuing it.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] It is often named after the target side: e.g.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] *top* is the value of the element at the top of the deque.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] In the context of the functional programming, the *dequeue* operation (that returns two values: the removed element and the new deque) is not used.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] It is replaced by a *peek* function (i.e.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] *head* and *last*) and a function that returns the deque minus the end, i.e.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] There are at least two common ways to efficiently implement a deque, that are often pitted against one another: with a doubly linked list or with a modified dynamic array.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] There are many variations and actual implementations are often hybrid solutions.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Additionally, several purely functional implementations of the double-ended queue exist.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] While a simple list may implement a deque, a doubly-linked list is more adequate for its symmetry to achieve a fast access to both ends of the list (*head* and *tail*, hence the name *head-tail linked list*).
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] The obvious solution is to manage two references; alternatively the deque can be built as a circular list.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] In a doubly-linked list implementation, and assuming no allocation/deallocation overhead, the time complexity of all deque operations is O(1).
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Additionally, insertion or deletion in the middle, given an iterator, can also be achieved in constant time; however, the time taken for random access by index is O(n).
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Similarly, finding a specific element normally requires O(n) time.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Linked data structures generally have poor locality of reference.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] In this case as well, while a dynamic array can be used to implement a deque, a variant that can grow from both ends is more appropriate.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] This is sometimes called *array deques*.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] The *amortized* time complexity of all deque operations with an *array deque* is O(1), thanks to the geometric expansion of the back-end buffer.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Additionally, random access by index takes constant time ; but the average time taken for insertion or deletion in the middle are O(n).
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Thank to the fast random access, finding an element in an ordered array is time O(log n) (binary search).
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Each time the array is resized, the whole content is moved: the memory usage is then momentarily doubled (or more), and all direct (external) references to the content of the array are lost.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Doubly linked lists cannot be used as immutable data structures.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] And an immutable array would be highly inefficient (an array is often simulated by a tree).
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] A purely functional implementation of the deque can be based on stack, that is easily implemented with a singly linked list as an immutable and persistent structure.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] "Persistent lists with catenation via recursive slow-down".
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] *Proc. of the 27th annual ACM symposium on Theory of computing*.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] This last process could be rather complicated as it needs to be executed concurrently with other operations and completed before the next one, to achieve an amortized real-time complexity.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] The next step is to support the operations in O(1) *worst-case* time.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Another challenge is the real-time catenation of deques.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Okasaki gives a simple solution that uses lazy lists combined with memoization.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] The stack to stack balancing is then partially automatic by means of a precise scheduling of incremental functions.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] However some authors deem such algorithm as not purely functional since memoization is considered as a side effect.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] In this paper Kaplan and Tarjan also present an even more complex version that achieves catenation in real-time.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] However this description is mostly textual.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Pottier publish a verified implementation of this data structure (in OCaml and Rocq), alongside a formal description and detailed analysis of the algorithm.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] More generally, real-time catenation requires a deque is a tuple consisting mainly in two sub-structures, that themselves contain deques or compounds of deques.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] The linear spine of the non-catenable deque is then replaced by a *binary skeleton*.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Kaplan, Okasaki, and Tarjan produced a simpler, amortized version that can be implemented either using lazy evaluation or more efficiently using mutation in a broader but still restricted fashion.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Mihaescu and Tarjan created a simpler (but still highly complex) strictly purely functional implementation of catenable deques, and also a much simpler implementation of strictly purely functional non catenable deques, both of which have optimal worst-case bounds (not officially published).
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Ada's containers provides the generic packages `Ada.Containers.Vectors` and `Ada.Containers.Doubly_Linked_Lists`, for the dynamic array and linked list implementations, respectively.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] C++'s Standard Template Library provides the class templates `std::deque` and `std::list`, for the multiple array and linked list implementations, respectively.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] As of Java 6, Java's Collections Framework provides a new `Deque` interface that provides the functionality of insertion and removal at both ends.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] It is implemented by classes such as `ArrayDeque` (also new in Java 6) and `LinkedList`, providing the dynamic array and linked list implementations, respectively.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] However, the `ArrayDeque`, contrary to its name, does not support random access.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] JavaScript's Array prototype & Perl's arrays have native support for both removing (shift and pop) and adding (unshift and push) elements on both ends.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Python 2.4 introduced the `collections` module with support for deque objects.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] It is implemented using a doubly linked list of fixed-length subarrays.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] As of PHP 5.3, PHP's SPL extension contains the 'SplDoublyLinkedList' class that can be used to implement Deque datastructures.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Previously to make a Deque structure the array functions array_shift/unshift/pop/push had to be used instead.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] GHC's Data.Sequence module implements an efficient, functional deque structure in Haskell.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] The implementation uses 2–3 finger trees annotated with sizes.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Rust's `std::collections` includes VecDeque which implements a double-ended queue using a growable ring buffer.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] In 1965, before even the *deque* is named, a code excerpt from the *CTSS Technical notes* describes three subroutines that manipulate the queues of "users".
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Only the first two subroutines are actually executed but the idea of a less restricted queue is there and coded in a library.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] A double-ended queue can always be substituted for a queue or a stack structure.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Thus real-world applications of the deque are often extended versions of stack- or queue-based algorithms.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Actually many applications only need an output- or (more rarely) input-restricted deque.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Only real-world applications that are optimally based on strict deque, i.e. which only need access to the elements at both ends and one by one, are listed here.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] An input-restricted deque can be used to build a *monotonic queue*, i.e. a sub-sequence whom elements are in given order, either increasing or decreasing.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Given a sequence, the algorithm only keeps elements in the desired order and discards the other ones.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] The elements of the monotonic sequence can then be dequeued from the other side (hence the usage of a deque).
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] A monotonic queue can be used to find the minimum or maximum value in a sliding window over a sequence in a linear time complexity.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] The complexity of a naive solution is O(n.k) time and O(1) space, where *n* is the length of the input sequence and *k* the size of the window.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] A solution that uses some kind of search method is O(n.log n) time and O(n) space.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] In the following code, the monotonic queue stores references to the elements of the sequence.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Each element of the input sequence is pushed and popped at most once resulting in 2.n operations.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] The space complexity is O(k), the maximum size of the deque.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] In a similar way a monotonic queue allows the optimization of some dynamic programming cases equivalent to the *least-weight sub-sequence* problem : shortest path problem for a weighted directed graph, paragraph breaking, etc.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] These problems are said to be *convex* or *concave*, and then *monotonic*.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] The time complexity is then reduced from O(n2) to O(n.log n), and O(n) in conducive situations.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] An other direct application of the monotonic queue is the **minimum queue** or **minqueue**.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] In this case the count of items in the window varies.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] The minqueue is a data structure with a *queue* interface that additionally gives a direct access to the minimum stored item.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] The key operations are then *enqueue*, *dequeue* and *find min*.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Despite the name alludes to the (min/max-) heap, the min/max-queue is not a priority queue: the order of the items is maintained from the enter to the exit (FIFO policy).
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] A simple version of a min-queue with O(1) amortized time is a normal queue combined with an auxiliary increasing monotonic queue, that gives the minimum item on its front.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] The addition of an item applies to both queues, and when the minimum item is dequeued from the normal queue (i.e. same front item), it is also dequeued from the monotonic queue.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Melkman's algorithm computes the convex hull of a simple polygonal chain (or a simple polygon) in linear time.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] The main difference with other similar algorithm is that Melkman requires vertices to be added on removed on both ends of the forming hull chain.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] The algorithm computes the position of each new vertex relative to the first and last segments (two vertices each) of the hull chain (stored in the deque).
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] The vertex is either ignored or added (enqueued) to both sides of the deque (the hull is a loop), after removing (dequeueing) some previous vertices that are now on the inner side of the hull.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Stacks and queues can be seen as a particular kinds of priority queues, with the priority determined by the order in which the elements are inserted.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Similarly a deque can implement a priority queue with two levels of priority: high priority elements are added to the front side of the deque while low priority ones are added to the rear.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Unless an element could be canceled or stolen and then ejected from the bottom, an output-restricted deque is adequate.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] Thus it's possible to modify the standard Dijkstra's algorithm to find single source shortest path in a graph with 0-cost and 1-cost edges.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] A deque substitutes the min-priority queue.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] 0-cost elements are enqueued in front of the deque (high-priority) and then are always processed before the higher cost elements (low-priority) that are enqueued at the rear end.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] A deque is used in the work stealing algorithm.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] This algorithm implements task scheduling for several processors.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] A separate deque with threads to be executed is maintained for each processor.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] To execute the next thread, the processor gets the first element from the deque (using the "remove first element" deque operation).
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] If the current thread forks, it is put back to the front of the deque ("insert element at front") and a new thread is executed.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] When one of the processors finishes execution of its own threads (i.e. its deque is empty), it can "steal" a thread from another processor: it gets the last element from the deque of another processor ("remove last element") and executes it.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] The work stealing algorithm is used by Intel's Threading Building Blocks (TBB) library for parallel programming.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] A Deque automaton (DA) is a finite-state machine equipped with a deque auxiliary memory.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] It generalizes Pushdown automaton (PDA) (stack automaton) and Queue automaton (Pull up automaton, PUA).
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] As such it is equivalent to a Turing machine, and therefore it can process the same class of formal languages.
[src:resizable-array-structure/double-ended-queue] But unlike the PDA and the PUA which impose serialization, a deque automaton permits parallel or interleaved execution of some operations.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] In computer science, a **dynamic array**, **growable array**, **resizable array**, **dynamic table**, **mutable array**, or **array list** is a random access, variable-size list data structure that allows elements to be added or removed.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] It is supplied with standard libraries in many modern mainstream programming languages.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] Dynamic arrays overcome a limit of static arrays, which have a fixed capacity that needs to be specified at allocation.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] A dynamic array is not the same thing as a dynamically allocated array or variable-length array, either of which is an array whose size is fixed when the array is allocated, although a dynamic array may use such a fixed-size array as a back end.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] A simple dynamic array can be constructed by allocating an array of fixed-size, typically larger than the number of elements immediately required.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] The elements of the dynamic array are stored contiguously at the start of the underlying array, and the remaining positions towards the end of the underlying array are reserved.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] Elements can be added at the end of a dynamic array in constant time by using the reserved space until this space is completely consumed.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] When all space is consumed and an additional element is to be added, the underlying fixed-size array needs to be increased in size.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] Typically, resizing is expensive because it involves allocating a new underlying array and possibly copying each element from the original array.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] Elements can be removed from the end of a dynamic array in constant time, as no resizing is required.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] The number of elements used by the dynamic array contents is its *logical size* or *length*, while the size of the underlying array is called the dynamic array's *physical size* or *capacity*.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] The capacity is the maximum possible size without relocating data.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] A fixed-size array will suffice in applications where the maximum logical size is fixed (e.g. by specification), or can be calculated before the array is allocated.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] To avoid incurring the cost of resizing many times, dynamic arrays resize by a large amount, such as doubling in size, and use the reserved space for future expansion.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] As *n* elements are inserted, the capacities form a geometric progression.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] Expanding the array by any constant proportion *a* ensures that inserting *n* elements takes *O*(*n*) time overall, meaning that each insertion takes amortized constant time (so long as any given allocation takes *O*(*1*) time).
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] Many dynamic arrays also deallocate some of the underlying storage if its size drops below a certain threshold, such as 30% of the capacity.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] This threshold must be strictly smaller than 1/*a* in order to provide hysteresis (provide a stable band to avoid repeatedly growing and shrinking) and support mixed sequences of insertions and removals with amortized constant cost.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] Dynamic arrays are a common example when teaching amortized analysis.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] The growth factor for the dynamic array depends on several factors including a space-time trade-off and algorithms used in the memory allocator itself.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] For growth factor *a*, the average time per insertion operation is about *a*/(*a*−1), while the number of wasted cells is bounded above by (*a*−1)*n*.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] If memory allocator uses a first-fit allocation algorithm, then growth factor values such as *a*=2 can cause dynamic array expansion to run out of memory even though a significant amount of memory may still be available.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] There have been various discussions on ideal growth factor values, including proposals for the golden ratio as well as the value 1.5.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] Many textbooks, however, use *a* = 2 for simplicity and analysis purposes.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] Dynamic arrays benefit from many of the advantages of arrays, including good locality of reference and data cache utilization, compactness (low memory use), and random access.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] They usually have only a small fixed additional overhead for storing information about the size and capacity.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] This makes dynamic arrays an attractive tool for building cache-friendly data structures.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] However, in languages like Python or Java that enforce reference semantics, the dynamic array generally will not store the actual data, but rather it will store references to the data that resides in other areas of memory.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] In this case, accessing items in the array sequentially will actually involve accessing multiple non-contiguous areas of memory, so the many advantages of the cache-friendliness of this data structure are lost.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] This disadvantage is mitigated by the gap buffer and *tiered vector* variants discussed under *Variants* below.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] Also, in a highly fragmented memory region, it may be expensive or impossible to find contiguous space for a large dynamic array, whereas linked lists do not require the whole data structure to be stored contiguously.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] Gap buffers are similar to dynamic arrays but allow efficient insertion and deletion operations clustered near the same arbitrary location.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] Some deque implementations use array deques, which allow amortized constant time insertion/removal at both ends, instead of just one end.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] Goodrich presented a dynamic array algorithm called *tiered vectors* that provides *O*(*n*1/*k*) performance for insertions and deletions from anywhere in the array, and *O*(*k*) get and set, where *k* ≥ 2 is a constant parameter.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] Hashed array tree (HAT) is a dynamic array algorithm published by Sitarski in 1996.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] Hashed array tree wastes order *n*1/2 amount of storage space, where *n* is the number of elements in the array.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] The algorithm has *O*(1) amortized performance when appending a series of objects to the end of a hashed array tree.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] In a 1999 paper, Brodnik et al. describe a tiered dynamic array data structure, which wastes only *n*1/2 space for *n* elements at any point in time, and they prove a lower bound showing that any dynamic array must waste this much space if the operations are to remain amortized constant time.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] Additionally, they present a variant where growing and shrinking the buffer has not only amortized but worst-case constant time.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] Bagwell (2002) presented the VList algorithm, which can be adapted to implement a dynamic array.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] Naïve resizable arrays—also called "the worst implementation" of resizable arrays—keep the allocated size of the array exactly big enough for all the data it contains, perhaps by calling realloc for each and every item added to the array.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] Naïve resizable arrays are the simplest way of implementing a resizable array in C.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] They don't waste any memory, but appending to the end of the array always takes Θ(*n*) time.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] Linearly growing arrays pre-allocate ("waste") Θ(1) space every time they re-size the array, making them many times faster than naïve resizable arrays—appending to the end of the array still takes Θ(*n*) time but with a much smaller constant.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] Naïve resizable arrays and linearly growing arrays may be useful when a space-constrained application needs lots of small resizable arrays; they are also commonly used as an educational example leading to exponentially growing dynamic arrays.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] C++'s `std::vector` and Rust's `std::vec::Vec` are implementations of dynamic arrays, as are `java.util.ArrayList` in Java and `System.Collections.ArrayList` in the .NET Framework.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] The generic `System.Collections.Generic.List<T>` class in version 2.0 of the .NET Framework is also implemented with dynamic arrays.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] Smalltalk's `OrderedCollection` is a dynamic array with dynamic start and end-index, making the removal of the first element also O(1).
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] Python's `list` datatype implementation is a dynamic array, the growth pattern of which is: 0, 4, 8, 16, 24, 32, 40, 52, 64, 76, ...
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] Delphi and D implement dynamic arrays at the language's core.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] Ada's `Ada.Containers.Vectors` generic package provides dynamic array implementation for a given subtype.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] Many scripting languages such as Perl and Ruby offer dynamic arrays as a built-in primitive data type.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] Several cross-platform frameworks provide dynamic array implementations for C, including `CFArray` and `CFMutableArray` in Core Foundation, and `GArray` and `GPtrArray` in GLib.
[src:resizable-array-structure/dynamic-array] Common Lisp provides a rudimentary support for resizable vectors by allowing to configure the built-in `array` type as *adjustable* and the location of insertion by the *fill-pointer*.
[src:resizable-array-structure/hashed-array-tree] Its primary objective is to reduce the amount of element copying due to automatic array resizing operations, and to improve memory usage patterns.
[src:resizable-array-structure/hashed-array-tree] Whereas simple dynamic arrays based on geometric expansion waste linear (Ω(*n*)) space, where *n* is the number of elements in the array, hashed array trees waste only order *O*(√*n*) storage space.
[src:resizable-array-structure/hashed-array-tree] An optimization of the algorithm allows elimination of data copying completely, at a cost of increasing the wasted space.
[src:resizable-array-structure/hashed-array-tree] It can perform access in constant (O(1)) time, though slightly slower than simple dynamic arrays.
[src:resizable-array-structure/hashed-array-tree] The algorithm has O(1) amortized performance when appending a series of objects to the end of a hashed array tree.
[src:resizable-array-structure/hashed-array-tree] Contrary to its name, it does not use hash functions.
[src:resizable-array-structure/hashed-array-tree] As defined by Sitarski, a hashed array tree has a top-level directory containing a power of two number of leaf arrays.
[src:resizable-array-structure/hashed-array-tree] All leaf arrays are the same size as the top-level directory.
[src:resizable-array-structure/hashed-array-tree] This structure superficially resembles a hash table with array-based collision chains, which is the basis for the name *hashed array tree*.
[src:resizable-array-structure/hashed-array-tree] A full hashed array tree can hold *m*2 elements, where *m* is the size of the top-level directory.
[src:resizable-array-structure/hashed-array-tree] The use of powers of two enables faster physical addressing through bit operations instead of arithmetic operations of quotient and remainder and ensures the O(1) amortized performance of append operation in the presence of occasional global array copy while expanding.
[src:resizable-array-structure/hashed-array-tree] In a usual dynamic array geometric expansion scheme, the array is reallocated as a whole sequential chunk of memory with the new size a double of its current size (and the whole data is then moved to the new location).
[src:resizable-array-structure/hashed-array-tree] This ensures O(1) amortized operations at a cost of O(n) wasted space, as the enlarged array is filled to the half of its new capacity.
[src:resizable-array-structure/hashed-array-tree] When a hashed array tree is full, its directory and leaves must be restructured to twice their prior size to accommodate additional append operations.
[src:resizable-array-structure/hashed-array-tree] The data held in old structure is then moved into the new locations.
[src:resizable-array-structure/hashed-array-tree] Only one new leaf is then allocated and added into the top array which thus becomes filled only to a quarter of its new capacity.
[src:resizable-array-structure/hashed-array-tree] All the extra leaves are not allocated yet, and will only be allocated when needed, thus wasting only *O*(√*n*) of storage.
[src:resizable-array-structure/hashed-array-tree] There are multiple alternatives for reducing size: when a hashed array tree is one eighth full, it can be restructured to a smaller, half-full hashed array tree; another option is only freeing unused leaf arrays, without resizing the leaves.
[src:resizable-array-structure/hashed-array-tree] Further optimizations include adding new leaves without resizing while growing the directory array as needed, possibly through geometric expansion.
[src:resizable-array-structure/hashed-array-tree] This will eliminate the need for data copying completely at the cost of making the wasted space be *O*(*n*), with a small constant, and only performing restructuring when a set threshold overhead is reached.
[src:resizable-array-structure/hashed-array-tree] Brodnik et al. presented a dynamic array algorithm with a similar space wastage profile to hashed array trees.
[src:resizable-array-structure/hashed-array-tree] Brodnik's implementation retains previously allocated leaf arrays, with a more complicated address calculation function as compared to hashed array trees.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] In numerical analysis and scientific computing, a **sparse matrix** or **sparse array** is a matrix in which most of the elements are zero.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] There is no strict definition regarding the proportion of zero-value elements for a matrix to qualify as **sparse** but a common criterion is that the number of non-zero elements is roughly equal to the number of rows or columns.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] By contrast, if most of the elements are non-zero, the matrix is considered **dense**.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] The number of zero-valued elements divided by the total number of elements (e.g., *m* × *n* for an *m* × *n* matrix) is sometimes referred to as the **sparsity** of the matrix.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] Conceptually, sparsity corresponds to systems with few pairwise interactions.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] For example, consider a line of balls connected by springs from one to the next: this is a sparse system, as only adjacent balls are coupled.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] By contrast, if the same line of balls were to have springs connecting each ball to all other balls, the system would correspond to a dense matrix.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] The concept of sparsity is useful in combinatorics and application areas such as network theory and numerical analysis, which typically have a low density of significant data or connections.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] Large sparse matrices often appear in scientific or engineering applications when solving partial differential equations.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] When storing and manipulating sparse matrices on a computer, it is beneficial and often necessary to use specialized algorithms and data structures that take advantage of the sparse structure of the matrix.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] Specialized computers have been made for sparse matrices, as they are common in the machine learning field.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] Operations using standard dense-matrix structures and algorithms are slow and inefficient when applied to large sparse matrices as processing and memory are wasted on the zeros.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] Sparse data is by nature more easily compressed and thus requires significantly less storage.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] Some very large sparse matrices are infeasible to manipulate using standard dense-matrix algorithms.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] The band matrices form a special class of sparse matrix where the non-zero elements are concentrated near the main diagonal.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] A band matrix is characterised by its lower and upper bandwidths, which refer to the number of diagonals below and above (respectively) the main diagonal between which all of the non-zero entries are contained.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] Formally, the lower bandwidth of a matrix **A** is the smallest number *p* such that the entry *a**i*,*j* vanishes whenever *i* > *j* + *p*.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] Similarly, the upper bandwidth is the smallest number *p* such that *a**i*,*j* = 0 whenever *i* < *j* − *p* (Golub & Van Loan 1996, §1.2.1).
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] For example, a tridiagonal matrix has lower bandwidth 1 and upper bandwidth 1.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] As another example, the following sparse matrix has lower and upper bandwidth both equal to 3.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] Matrices with reasonably small upper and lower bandwidth are known as band matrices and often lend themselves to simpler algorithms than general sparse matrices; or one can sometimes apply dense matrix algorithms and gain efficiency simply by looping over a reduced number of indices.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] By rearranging the rows and columns of a matrix **A** it may be possible to obtain a matrix **A**′ with a lower bandwidth.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] A number of algorithms are designed for bandwidth minimization.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] A diagonal matrix is the extreme case of a band matrix, with zero upper and lower bandwidth.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] A diagonal matrix can be stored efficiently by storing just the entries in the main diagonal as a one-dimensional array, so a diagonal *n* × *n* matrix requires only *n* entries in memory.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] A symmetric sparse matrix arises as the adjacency matrix of an undirected graph; it can be stored efficiently as an adjacency list.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] A block-diagonal matrix consists of sub-matrices along its diagonal blocks.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] The *fill-in* of a matrix are those entries that change from an initial zero to a non-zero value during the execution of an algorithm.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] To reduce the memory requirements and the number of arithmetic operations used during an algorithm, it is useful to minimize the fill-in by switching rows and columns in the matrix.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] The symbolic Cholesky decomposition can be used to calculate the worst possible fill-in before doing the actual Cholesky decomposition.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] There are other methods than the Cholesky decomposition in use.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] Orthogonalization methods (such as QR factorization) are common, for example, when solving problems by least squares methods.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] While the theoretical fill-in is still the same, in practical terms the "false non-zeros" can be different for different methods.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] And symbolic versions of those algorithms can be used in the same manner as the symbolic Cholesky to compute worst case fill-in.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] Both iterative and direct methods exist for sparse matrix solving.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] Iterative methods, such as conjugate gradient method and GMRES utilize fast computations of matrix-vector products $Ax_{i}$ , where matrix A is sparse.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] The use of preconditioners can significantly accelerate convergence of such iterative methods.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] A matrix is typically stored as a two-dimensional array.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] Each entry in the array represents an element *a**i*,*j* of the matrix and is accessed by the two indices *i* and *j*.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] Conventionally, *i* is the row index, numbered from top to bottom, and *j* is the column index, numbered from left to right.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] For an *m* × *n* matrix, the amount of memory required to store the matrix in this format is proportional to *m* × *n* (disregarding the fact that the dimensions of the matrix also need to be stored).
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] In the case of a sparse matrix, substantial memory requirement reductions can be realized by storing only the non-zero entries.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] Depending on the number and distribution of the non-zero entries, different data structures can be used and yield huge savings in memory when compared to the basic approach.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] The trade-off is that accessing the individual elements becomes more complex and additional structures are needed to be able to recover the original matrix unambiguously.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] DOK consists of a dictionary that maps (row, column)-pairs to the value of the elements.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] Elements that are missing from the dictionary are taken to be zero.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] The format is good for incrementally constructing a sparse matrix in random order, but poor for iterating over non-zero values in lexicographical order.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] One typically constructs a matrix in this format and then converts to another more efficient format for processing.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] LIL stores one list per row, with each entry containing the column index and the value.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] Typically, these entries are kept sorted by column index for faster lookup.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] This is another format good for incremental matrix construction.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] COO stores a list of (row, column, value) tuples.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] Ideally, the entries are sorted first by row index and then by column index, to improve random access times.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] This is another format that is good for incremental matrix construction.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] The *compressed sparse row* (CSR) or *compressed row storage* (CRS) or Yale format represents a matrix **M** by three (one-dimensional) arrays, that respectively contain nonzero values, the extents of rows, and column indices.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] It is similar to COO, but compresses the row indices, hence the name.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] This format allows fast row access and matrix-vector multiplications (**M***x*).
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] The CSR format has been in use since at least the mid-1960s, with the first complete description appearing in 1967.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] The CSR format stores a sparse *m* × *n* matrix **M** in row form using three (one-dimensional) arrays (V, COL_INDEX, ROW_INDEX).
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] Let NNZ denote the number of nonzero entries in **M**.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] Then we take slices from V and COL_INDEX starting at row_start and ending at row_end.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] To extract the row 1 (the second row) of this matrix we set `row_start=1` and `row_end=2`.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] We now know that in row 1 we have one element at column 1 with value 8.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] In this case the CSR representation contains 13 entries, compared to 16 in the original matrix.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] The CSR format saves on memory only when NNZ < (*m* (*n* − 1) − 1) / 2.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] The whole is stored as 21 entries: 8 in V, 8 in COL_INDEX, and 5 in ROW_INDEX.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] Note that in this format, the first value of ROW_INDEX is always zero and the last is always NNZ, so they are in some sense redundant (although in programming languages where the array length needs to be explicitly stored, NNZ would not be redundant).
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] Nonetheless, this does avoid the need to handle an exceptional case when computing the length of each row, as it guarantees the formula ROW_INDEX[*i* + 1] − ROW_INDEX[*i*] works for any row *i*.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] Moreover, the memory cost of this redundant storage is likely insignificant for a sufficiently large matrix.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] The (old and new) Yale sparse matrix formats are instances of the CSR scheme.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] The old Yale format works exactly as described above, with three arrays; the new format combines ROW_INDEX and COL_INDEX into a single array and handles the diagonal of the matrix separately.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] For logical adjacency matrices, the data array can be omitted, as the existence of an entry in the row array is sufficient to model a binary adjacency relation.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] It is likely known as the Yale format because it was proposed in the 1977 Yale Sparse Matrix Package report from Department of Computer Science at Yale University.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] CSC is similar to CSR except that values are read first by column, a row index is stored for each value, and column pointers are stored.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] For example, CSC is (val, row_ind, col_ptr), where val is an array of the (top-to-bottom, then left-to-right) non-zero values of the matrix; row_ind is the row indices corresponding to the values; and, col_ptr is the list of val indexes where each column starts.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] The name is based on the fact that column index information is compressed relative to the COO format.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] One typically uses another format (LIL, DOK, COO) for construction.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] This format is efficient for arithmetic operations, column slicing, and matrix-vector products.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] This is the traditional format for specifying a sparse matrix in MATLAB (via the `sparse` function).
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] Many software libraries support sparse matrices, and provide solvers for sparse matrix equations.
[src:resizable-array-structure/sparse-matrix] The term *sparse matrix* was possibly coined by Harry Markowitz who initiated some pioneering work but then left the field.
